  "@type": "Article",
  "dateModified": "2026-03-03",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-03",
  "description": "Property is not a thing but a social relation. When someone says they \u0026ldquo;own\u0026rdquo; a piece of land, they don\u0026rsquo;t mean they have a physical bond with the dirt. They mean that a community, a legal system, or a state recognizes their right to use that land, to exclude others from it, and to sell or transfer it. Property is a set of rights enforced between people — a relation between an owner, a thing, and everyone else who is obligated to respect that claim. Without enforcement, ownership is just assertion.\n",
